02283cam a22003734a 20161228111824.0m     o  d        cr unu||||||||120619s2012    miu     o    s000 0 eng d  a2012023854  a9780472071852q(hardback)  a9780472051854q(paper)  a9780472028948q(e-book)7 a10.3998/mpub.4348618  aMiUbengcMiU  an-us---00aPN1059.A9bH85 201200a808.12231 aHummer, T. R.10aAvailable surfaces :bessays on poesis /cT.R. Hummer. 1aAnn Arbor :bUniversity of Michigan Press,cc2012.  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier1 aPoets on poetry  a"T. R. Hummer grew up in the Deep South and planned to become a musician before he met poetry. This musical influence is visible in his work: he often discusses poetry together with music (and sometimes the other way around), and his career has included both writing and performance. The present volume, Available Surfaces, focuses on the art of making both poetry and music and on the concept of "making" as well. Hummer draws on childhood experiences ("A Length of Hemp Rope"), adult experiences ("Hotel California"), experiences as a poet ("Available Surfaces"), and experiences as an explorer of unworldly spaces ("The Hive," "Brain Wave and the End of Science Fiction"). Hummer has published ten volumes of poetry with presses including Louisiana State University Press and the University of Illinois Press. His work has appeared in two anthology volumes published by Simon & Schuster and Cengage and in two Pushcart Prize anthologies. He has edited the Kenyon Review, the Georgia Review, and the Cimarron Review, among other journals. "--cProvided by publisher.  aDescription based on information from the publisher. 0aPoetryxAuthorship. 0aPoetics. 4aElectronic books.2 aMichigan Publishing (University of Michigan)epublisher. 0aPoets on poetry40zAccess to the Michigan Publishing online version:uhttps://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.4348618